President Joe Biden has declared a state of emergency in Kentucky due to severe storms, straight-line winds, flooding, and tornadoes that began on December 10, 2021. This declaration allows the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) to coordinate disaster relief efforts and provide assistance to the affected areas. FEMA is authorized to mobilize equipment and resources to alleviate the impacts of the emergency, with emergency protective measures funded at 75 percent by the federal government. John Brogan has been named as the Federal Coordinating Officer for recovery operations in the affected areas. For more information, the media can contact the FEMA News Desk.